WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.052 --> 00:00:08.760
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon, and welcome

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:12.150
to Talks at Google in
Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:12.150 --> 00:00:14.630
Today it is my
very great pleasure

00:00:14.630 --> 00:00:18.680
to introduce one of my
favorite writers, Brock Clarke.

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:22.020
Brock is the author of
six books, most recently,

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:24.060
"The Happiest People
in the World,"

00:00:24.060 --> 00:00:26.420
and "An Arsonist's
Guide to Writers' Homes

00:00:26.420 --> 00:00:29.605
in New England," which
was a national bestseller

00:00:29.605 --> 00:00:33.060
and has appeared in a
dozen foreign editions.

00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:35.710
His stories and essays
have appeared in a number

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:38.530
of prestigious publications.

00:00:38.530 --> 00:00:42.680
He received a national Endowment
for the Arts fellowship in 2008

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:46.410
and has twice been a finalist
for the National Magazine Award

00:00:46.410 --> 00:00:47.700
for Fiction.

00:00:47.700 --> 00:00:51.880
He teaches creative
writing at Bowdoin College.

00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:54.580
In addition, he is one
of my favorite writers.

00:00:54.580 --> 00:00:55.220
I admit it.

00:00:55.220 --> 00:00:58.120
I'm an unabashed fan boy.

00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:00.990
I promised I wouldn't
gush, so that's it.

00:01:00.990 --> 00:01:03.555
I find his fiction
simultaneously heartbreaking

00:01:03.555 --> 00:01:06.200
and uplifting, and I
don't feel the same

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:09.420
about the world or
myself after finishing

00:01:09.420 --> 00:01:11.910
one of his darkly funny novels.

00:01:11.910 --> 00:01:15.400
Please join me in
welcoming Brock Clarke.

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:16.650
BROCK CLARKE: Thank you, John.

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:20.840
Hello.

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:22.360
Thank you for having me.

00:01:22.360 --> 00:01:24.510
Thank you for coming.

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:26.272
I'm going to read
from this new book.

00:01:26.272 --> 00:01:28.230
It's called "The Happiest
People in the World."

00:01:28.230 --> 00:01:29.382
Can you all hear me OK?

00:01:29.382 --> 00:01:31.340
I was told I have this
helpful note to project.

00:01:31.340 --> 00:01:33.380
But I also have a
terrible history

00:01:33.380 --> 00:01:36.890
with microphones, feedback,
people weeping in front rows,

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:37.390
fleeing.

00:01:37.390 --> 00:01:40.190
So I'll try hard not to
replicate that experience.

00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:43.147
Anyways, this book is
called "The Happiest People

00:01:43.147 --> 00:01:43.730
in the World."

00:01:43.730 --> 00:01:47.160
And the origin is I
went to Denmark in 2005

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:49.130
with my-- my wife
had worked there.

00:01:49.130 --> 00:01:50.320
My wife, son, and I went.

00:01:50.320 --> 00:01:52.580
And before I went, I had
never even thought of Denmark

00:01:52.580 --> 00:01:54.270
as a place, let alone
a place I would go.

00:01:54.270 --> 00:01:55.686
I mean, when I
thought of Denmark,

00:01:55.686 --> 00:01:57.200
I thought of tulips
and windmills,

00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:59.810
which meant when I thought of
Denmark, I thought of Holland.

00:01:59.810 --> 00:02:01.120
It's an entirely
different country.

00:02:01.120 --> 00:02:02.460
That's how little
I thought about it.

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:03.442
And when I went
there, I absolutely

00:02:03.442 --> 00:02:05.120
fell in love with
the place the way

00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:07.300
I do, at least, with the
most unlikely places,

00:02:07.300 --> 00:02:09.149
the least likely places.

00:02:09.149 --> 00:02:10.190
I was really happy there.

00:02:10.190 --> 00:02:11.912
I thought of this
place as the place

00:02:11.912 --> 00:02:13.620
that I could live and
be a different kind

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:15.911
of Brock Clarke, which I
always desperately want to be.

00:02:15.911 --> 00:02:18.970
And anyways, I was forced
finally to go home.

00:02:18.970 --> 00:02:19.560
I had work.

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:20.400
My wife had work.

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:22.030
And I thought about
Denmark a lot.

00:02:22.030 --> 00:02:25.344
I kept thinking about it as this
sort of place that mysteriously

00:02:25.344 --> 00:02:26.260
meant something to me.

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:28.790
And then not long after
that, these cartoonists

00:02:28.790 --> 00:02:32.532
for "Jyllands-Posten," which
is a newspaper in Copenhagen,

00:02:32.532 --> 00:02:34.990
were asked to draw cartoons of
the prophet Muhammad as they

00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:35.750
saw him.

00:02:35.750 --> 00:02:36.960
And they did that.

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:39.642
And one of them, in particular,
drew this cartoon of Muhammad

00:02:39.642 --> 00:02:40.850
with a bomb under his turban.

00:02:40.850 --> 00:02:43.307
And some of the expected
things happened.

00:02:43.307 --> 00:02:44.640
And I began to think about this.

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:47.090
The Danes are always called the
happiest people in the world.

00:02:47.090 --> 00:02:49.100
They're found by these studies
to be the happiest people

00:02:49.100 --> 00:02:49.850
in the world.

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:52.620
And I'd wondered about that
weird intersection of people

00:02:52.620 --> 00:02:55.010
who are supposedly happy
making other people

00:02:55.010 --> 00:02:57.925
in their same country
profoundly unhappy.

00:02:57.925 --> 00:02:59.300
And as usual,
because writers are

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:01.260
among the most mercenary
people in the world,

00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:04.567
I tried to figure out how I
can make this into a novel.

00:03:04.567 --> 00:03:05.900
I could get something out of it.

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:08.358
So what I decided to do-- and
I could talk about this later

00:03:08.358 --> 00:03:10.670
if any of you have
any questions-- was

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:14.790
to create a cartoonist, a
fictional cartoonist who then--

00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:17.080
well, you'll see-- a
fictional cartoonist

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:19.479
in this faraway place,
in Skagen, Denmark.

00:03:19.479 --> 00:03:21.020
What I'm going to
do in reading this,

00:03:21.020 --> 00:03:22.640
I'm going to read
an opening chapter.

00:03:22.640 --> 00:03:24.559
And then I'm going to
skip around a little bit

00:03:24.559 --> 00:03:27.100
to chase the novel with a number
of different points of view.

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:28.860
And then I'll wrap up.

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:31.470
And I'd be happy to answer
questions either along the way

00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:32.947
or at the end.

00:03:32.947 --> 00:03:33.780
So again, thank you.

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:35.330
Some swearing in here, as usual.

00:03:35.330 --> 00:03:36.082
I apologize.

00:03:36.082 --> 00:03:37.790
I've been doing my
best to keep it clean.

00:03:37.790 --> 00:03:40.170
I did this weird present--
I gave a reading at Clemson

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:41.700
University this past weekend.

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:43.782
I made the mistake
of agreeing to talk

00:03:43.782 --> 00:03:45.240
to a bunch of high
school students.

00:03:45.240 --> 00:03:47.780
And the thing I was talking
about, I couldn't clean it up.

00:03:47.780 --> 00:03:48.860
It would make no sense.

00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:51.960
And I pretty much got run out
of the state of South Carolina.

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:54.219
So I'm going to try really
hard to keep it cleaner,

00:03:54.219 --> 00:03:56.010
although I'm sure it
doesn't matter to you.

00:03:56.010 --> 00:03:58.740
OK.

00:03:58.740 --> 00:04:01.590
"What is only slightly less
well-known is that soon after

00:04:01.590 --> 00:04:03.670
the first Danish
Embassy was torched,

00:04:03.670 --> 00:04:05.470
soon after the
first death threat,

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:08.360
soon after the first attempted
murder of the cartoonist,

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:12.490
the editor of a newspaper, the
'Optimist,' in Skagen, Denmark,

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:15.560
asked his staff cartoonist,
he had only one--

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:18.269
it was a weekly newspaper
with a small circulation--

00:04:18.269 --> 00:04:21.110
to draw a cartoon depicting
in some way or other

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:25.450
the controversy over the by now
infamous cartoons of Muhammad.

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:27.380
'Me?' the cartoonist asked.

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:29.080
His name was Jens Baedrup.

00:04:29.080 --> 00:04:31.500
He'd worked at the
paper for nine years.

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:34.460
Mostly he drew cartoons of
local interest, tourists eating

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:38.080
hot dogs, while walking too
slowly in the pedestrian mall,

00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:39.820
grizzled fishermen
acting surprised

00:04:39.820 --> 00:04:43.370
at seeing fish they just caught
on display at the market,

00:04:43.370 --> 00:04:45.500
as though to say, what
are you doing here?

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:48.690
Scanians caught in bad weather
and making the best of it.

00:04:48.690 --> 00:04:52.050
In fact, his most recent cartoon
had been of a man and a woman

00:04:52.050 --> 00:04:53.780
standing under a
roof and the man

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:56.460
saying, 'At least, we have
a roof over our heads'

00:04:56.460 --> 00:04:58.060
and the woman not
saying anything,

00:04:58.060 --> 00:05:01.680
just looking miserable because
she was drenched and so was he,

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:03.610
because the rain was
blowing sideways,

00:05:03.610 --> 00:05:07.010
and the roof structure they were
standing under had no walls.

00:05:07.010 --> 00:05:10.770
'Yes, you.' 'Why?'
the cartoonist asked.

00:05:10.770 --> 00:05:13.370
Of course, he'd been following
the whole thing on television,

00:05:13.370 --> 00:05:15.310
on the radio, in the newspaper.

00:05:15.310 --> 00:05:17.810
It made him anxious,
angry, annoyed,

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:20.470
the way things do when you
don't know whom to blame.

00:05:20.470 --> 00:05:22.690
But then again, these
cartoons had been published

00:05:22.690 --> 00:05:24.180
in a Copenhagen newspaper.

00:05:24.180 --> 00:05:26.140
And Skagen was as far
away from Copenhagen

00:05:26.140 --> 00:05:27.890
as you could get and
still be in Denmark."

00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:30.170
Anyone here ever been to
Skagen, he asked lamely.

00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:30.670
No.

00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:32.360
So Denmark's like
a tip of a finger.

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:35.375
And the very tip
ending east is Skagen.

00:05:35.375 --> 00:05:36.750
And so I looked
on the map, and I

00:05:36.750 --> 00:05:38.450
thought, where is
the furthest place

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:39.960
you could get in this
country where you could not

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:40.640
escape from?

00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:42.190
And then I chose that place.

00:05:42.190 --> 00:05:45.190
That's Skagen.

00:05:45.190 --> 00:05:47.550
"In fact it was common
for people in Skagen,

00:05:47.550 --> 00:05:49.630
after learning of some
outrageous news coming out

00:05:49.630 --> 00:05:52.090
of the nation's capital
five hours to the south,

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:55.305
to shrug it off by saying,
but that's Copenhagen.

00:05:55.305 --> 00:05:57.810
'Because this is
important,' the editor said.

00:05:57.810 --> 00:05:59.310
'I think you'll do a good job.

00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:03.360
I can't think of anyone I rather
have do this job than you.'

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:04.900
The cartoonist
recognized that this

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:08.040
was tainted praise or at least
praise with an ulterior motive.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:10.440
But that did not mean
he was immune to it.

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:11.720
He thought for a minute.

00:06:11.720 --> 00:06:13.672
He would've asked
his wife her opinion.

00:06:13.672 --> 00:06:15.630
But she had gone to visit
her parents in Aarhus

00:06:15.630 --> 00:06:18.400
and wasn't due back in
Skagen for another week.

00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:20.690
He could have called her
on the phone, of course,

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:23.110
but things had not been
going too well with them.

00:06:23.110 --> 00:06:25.020
Lately, every
little disagreement

00:06:25.020 --> 00:06:27.150
threatened to turn into
a large argument, which

00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:28.910
then threatened to
turn into a referendum

00:06:28.910 --> 00:06:30.417
on the marriage itself.

00:06:30.417 --> 00:06:32.500
And one of the things they
most often argued about

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:34.840
was the cartoonist's
unshakable optimism,

00:06:34.840 --> 00:06:37.690
his belief that everything
was going to be just fine.

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:39.740
He knew if he
called and asked her

00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:41.510
whether he should
draw the cartoon,

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:43.052
she would question
his mental health.

00:06:43.052 --> 00:06:45.468
'I don't know what you're so
worried about,' he would then

00:06:45.468 --> 00:06:46.120
say.

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:48.300
I think everything's
going to be just fine.

00:06:48.300 --> 00:06:50.120
And then she would
mockingly call him

00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:53.520
the 'Skagen Optimist,' which
in addition to being the name

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:57.080
of the newspaper, was also the
name of the weekly cartoon.

00:06:57.080 --> 00:06:59.550
In fact, the cartoon of the
man and his wife getting

00:06:59.550 --> 00:07:01.400
wet from the sideways
rain had been

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:04.279
based on something that had
happened to them-- twice.

00:07:04.279 --> 00:07:06.820
The cartoonist thought that by
having the wife in the cartoon

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:08.790
remain silent--
in real life, she

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:11.390
had not remained silent--
his wife would not recognize

00:07:11.390 --> 00:07:13.000
herself in the cartoon.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.000
But this turned out to
be yet another example

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:16.880
of his over-optimism.

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:19.200
So instead of calling
his wife, the cartoonist

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:20.892
let his mind argue
with itself the way

00:07:20.892 --> 00:07:22.850
it does when it's about
to let you do something

00:07:22.850 --> 00:07:24.350
you'll later regret.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:27.030
'You really shouldn't
do this,' his mind said.

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:28.160
'But I'll do a good job.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:30.570
The editor said so
himself.' 'The editor is

00:07:30.570 --> 00:07:33.496
a liar.' 'Yes, but no one
is a liar all the time.'

00:07:33.496 --> 00:07:35.620
'But you don't even have
a strong opinion about all

00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:38.360
this.' 'Who better to draw a
cartoon like this than someone

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:41.130
who doesn't have a strong
opinion?' 'Tell that to people

00:07:41.130 --> 00:07:42.719
who have strong opinions.'

00:07:42.719 --> 00:07:44.010
'This is the "Skagen Optimist."

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:47.740
No one is ever going to see the
cartoon anyway.' 'Then why do

00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:51.090
it?' 'Because it's my job.'
And with that sentence,

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:53.820
a good many arguments that
should go on for much longer

00:07:53.820 --> 00:07:55.610
are brought to a close.

00:07:55.610 --> 00:07:57.520
'Fine,' the cartoonist
said to his editor.

00:07:57.520 --> 00:07:59.850
I'll do it.' 'Good,'
the editor said.

00:07:59.850 --> 00:08:02.470
'I'll need it before
you go home tonight.'

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:04.470
After receiving his
assignment, the cartoonist

00:08:04.470 --> 00:08:07.160
took a long walk through
Skagen, his heart narrating

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:08.090
his journey.

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:10.260
Skagen, the town
between two seas,

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:13.120
the town with the pretty yellow
houses with the red tile roofs

00:08:13.120 --> 00:08:15.350
and the neat yards, the
town with the wet wind

00:08:15.350 --> 00:08:18.640
and the cold sand, the town that
painters in the 19th century

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:21.570
made famous for its light, the
town where the eastward moving

00:08:21.570 --> 00:08:24.490
waves from the North Sea crash
into the westward moving waves

00:08:24.490 --> 00:08:27.110
from the Baltic, and the
spectacle is so great that even

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:30.440
the skeptical end up taking
too many pictures, the town so

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:33.929
orderly and good that even the
hulking tankers from Sweden,

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:36.260
and Norway, and
England, and Germany

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:40.159
patiently wait in lines that
stretch from one sea to another

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:42.659
before easing into the
docks at Skagen Havn,

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:45.344
the town where my parents
were born and where they died,

00:08:45.344 --> 00:08:47.510
the town where I was married
in the big white church

00:08:47.510 --> 00:08:50.051
with the little white clipper
ships dangling from the ceiling

00:08:50.051 --> 00:08:51.850
in between the
chandeliers, the town

00:08:51.850 --> 00:08:56.709
I have lived in for 42
years, the town I love.

00:08:56.709 --> 00:08:58.750
It is said that the Danes
are the happiest people

00:08:58.750 --> 00:09:01.275
in the world, and if that's
true then the people from Skagen

00:09:01.275 --> 00:09:03.390
are happier even than that.

00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:05.379
That was what the
cartoonist was feeling.

00:09:05.379 --> 00:09:07.420
And he was also feeling
that some of the cartoons

00:09:07.420 --> 00:09:09.860
in 'Jyllands-Posten'
had made him unhappy,

00:09:09.860 --> 00:09:12.130
and so had the violent
reactions to them,

00:09:12.130 --> 00:09:14.370
and now so had this assignment.

00:09:14.370 --> 00:09:16.280
That's when he got his idea.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.380
He went back to the
newspaper's office,

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:21.550
drew a cartoon featuring
a group of unhappy Danes.

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:24.660
One knew they were Danes because
they were frowning inexpertly,

00:09:24.660 --> 00:09:27.100
as if unhappiness had
come to them only recently

00:09:27.100 --> 00:09:28.850
and they didn't quite
know how to show it.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:31.650
And one also knew they were
Danes because they were white.

00:09:31.650 --> 00:09:34.210
And hovering over them
like an ominous cloud

00:09:34.210 --> 00:09:36.990
was the cartoonist's rendering
of the now infamous cartoon

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:39.340
of Muhammad with a
bomb in his turban.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:42.110
Once he was finished, Jens
handed the camera to his editor

00:09:42.110 --> 00:09:45.840
saying, 'I think this is
pretty good.' The editor looked

00:09:45.840 --> 00:09:46.910
at the cartoon.

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:49.100
He had been the newspaper's
editor for three years,

00:09:49.100 --> 00:09:52.360
and he hated the job, the
constant deadlines, the ink

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:55.060
everywhere, the reporters'
bad-tempered arguments

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:57.720
about what constituted good
grammar, the general sense

00:09:57.720 --> 00:10:00.430
of everything having been
much better yesterday.

00:10:00.430 --> 00:10:01.389
He could've just quit."

00:10:01.389 --> 00:10:03.055
I was a newspaper
journalist for a while

00:10:03.055 --> 00:10:04.550
so that's the one
thing I remember

00:10:04.550 --> 00:10:06.390
about being that thing.

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:08.600
"He could've just quit, but
the newspaper's publisher

00:10:08.600 --> 00:10:09.780
was his father.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:12.690
The paper had been owned and
run by his family for almost two

00:10:12.690 --> 00:10:13.572
centuries.

00:10:13.572 --> 00:10:15.280
Quitting the paper
would be like quitting

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:17.730
his family, something
that seemed less possible

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:19.064
the more he wanted it.

00:10:19.064 --> 00:10:21.230
The editor just hadn't been
able to figure a way out

00:10:21.230 --> 00:10:23.810
of the whole mess until now.

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:25.760
'I do think it's pretty
good,' the editor said

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:27.010
to the cartoonist.

00:10:27.010 --> 00:10:29.990
Then he published
it the next day.

00:10:29.990 --> 00:10:32.180
Less than a week later,
the 'Skagen Optimist'

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:35.030
decided, after someone had
thrown Molotov cocktails

00:10:35.030 --> 00:10:36.900
through its windows,
to shut down

00:10:36.900 --> 00:10:40.140
after nearly 200 years of
continuous publication.

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:43.070
Meanwhile, the cartoonist,
accompanied by agents

00:10:43.070 --> 00:10:45.470
from the Danish Security
and Intelligence Service

00:10:45.470 --> 00:10:47.970
had gone to his in-laws'
house in Aarhus.

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:49.770
His wife had met
him at the door.

00:10:49.770 --> 00:10:51.810
She knew by now
about the cartoon.

00:10:51.810 --> 00:10:55.240
It and the cartoonist had
made the television news.

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:57.320
She also knew about
the death threats.

00:10:57.320 --> 00:10:58.950
They'd made the news too.

00:10:58.950 --> 00:11:01.440
'Everything is going to be
just fine,' Jens had told her

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:04.280
repeatedly on the phone
over the previous week.

00:11:04.280 --> 00:11:07.440
'Oh, Jens,' she replied, 'What
were you thinking?' 'I was

00:11:07.440 --> 00:11:10.650
thinking everything was going
to be just fine,' he'd said.

00:11:10.650 --> 00:11:12.620
But she didn't know
yet about their house.

00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:15.030
Someone had set fire to
it six hours earlier.

00:11:15.030 --> 00:11:16.600
He told her about it.

00:11:16.600 --> 00:11:18.510
'Gone?' she said.

00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:20.360
'I'm sorry, Ilsa,' he said.

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:21.990
'Gone,' she repeated.

00:11:21.990 --> 00:11:23.680
Her eyes were far away.

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:27.190
He could see her seeing their
house, their marriage-- gone,

00:11:27.190 --> 00:11:27.990
gone.

00:11:27.990 --> 00:11:30.147
Skagen would be
gone for her too.

00:11:30.147 --> 00:11:31.980
Jens would always want
to go back to Skagen,

00:11:31.980 --> 00:11:34.560
but the agents told him he
wouldn't be able to because

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:36.100
of their plan for him.

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:38.420
Ilsa would be able to go
back there if she wanted,

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:39.840
but she wouldn't want to.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:41.320
She was from Aarhus.

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:42.510
That was her home.

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:44.950
For her, Skagen would
always be the small town

00:11:44.950 --> 00:11:47.200
with the burned down house
and the ruined marriage.

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:49.240
And that, to Jens, felt
like the worst thing

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:51.280
that had ever happened to him.

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:53.260
'Where will you
go?' she asked him.

00:11:53.260 --> 00:11:55.730
He cocked his head
toward the car idling

00:11:55.730 --> 00:11:57.300
in the street behind him.

00:11:57.300 --> 00:11:59.590
'They're figuring that
out right now,' he said.

00:11:59.590 --> 00:12:01.079
And then he told her the plan.

00:12:01.079 --> 00:12:03.120
The plan was for the agents
to announce that Jens

00:12:03.120 --> 00:12:04.760
had been killed in the fire.

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:06.680
The agents had recommended this.

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:08.310
They told Jens that
whoever had set

00:12:08.310 --> 00:12:11.960
the fire wouldn't stop trying
to kill him until he was dead.

00:12:11.960 --> 00:12:13.830
So they were, with
his permission,

00:12:13.830 --> 00:12:15.500
going to declare him dead.

00:12:15.500 --> 00:12:17.610
'It's the best way,'
Jens told Ilsa,

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:19.590
repeating what the
agents had told him.

00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:22.230
He looked to see whether
Ilsa understood all of this.

00:12:22.230 --> 00:12:25.120
She looked back at him
with big, solemn eyes.

00:12:25.120 --> 00:12:27.500
'What do I have
to do?' she asked.

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:29.600
'You have to act like
I'm dead,' he said.

00:12:29.600 --> 00:12:30.620
She nodded.

00:12:30.620 --> 00:12:32.820
'I can do that,' she said.

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:34.760
After that, neither
Jens nor Ilsa

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:36.390
seemed to know what to say.

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:38.376
Jens fought off the
urge to tell her again

00:12:38.376 --> 00:12:40.750
that everything would be just
fine, even though he really

00:12:40.750 --> 00:12:42.570
did believe that was true.

00:12:42.570 --> 00:12:44.400
He also fought off
the urge to tell her

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:47.220
that he was scared,
although that was true too.

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:49.810
Because what do you say when
a marriage ends like this?

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:52.761
Jens pictured a cartoon in
which a man and a woman--

00:12:52.761 --> 00:12:55.260
the woman's standing in front
of a burning house and the man

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:59.140
in front of an open grave--
handed oversize wedding rings

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:01.240
back to each other,
the woman saying,

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:03.070
'Well, that was a mistake.'

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:05.850
And then Jens turned,
walked to the agent's car,

00:13:05.850 --> 00:13:08.320
got into the backseat,
and closed the door.

00:13:08.320 --> 00:13:09.670
The car drove off.

00:13:09.670 --> 00:13:11.740
There were two agents
in the front seat.

00:13:11.740 --> 00:13:13.540
Jens was by himself in the back.

00:13:13.540 --> 00:13:15.960
After a moment, he said,
'That was horrible,

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:18.780
but I do think I got through
it fairly well.' But the agents

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:19.960
didn't respond.

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:21.830
Possibly, they didn't
hear Jens because he

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:24.456
was crying so hard as he
spoke, or because they

00:13:24.456 --> 00:13:25.830
were busy figuring
out where they

00:13:25.830 --> 00:13:29.331
were going to take him next,
where he was going to run."

00:13:29.331 --> 00:13:29.830
OK.

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:31.913
So the next chapter, which
I'm going to skip over,

00:13:31.913 --> 00:13:33.820
is from the point
of view of Tarik,

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:38.642
who's the young man who
burned down Jens's house.

00:13:38.642 --> 00:13:40.183
He's going to appear
in a chapter I'm

00:13:40.183 --> 00:13:41.450
going to read in a little bit.

00:13:41.450 --> 00:13:41.950
OK.

00:13:44.700 --> 00:13:47.690
"Two years later, as Jens
Baedrup was in one city--

00:13:47.690 --> 00:13:50.110
it was in Berlin, to
which he'd already run,

00:13:50.110 --> 00:13:52.630
preparing to run somewhere
else-- Jens asked

00:13:52.630 --> 00:13:55.880
the agent guarding him where
she would run if she were him.

00:13:55.880 --> 00:13:57.430
The agent was standing
at the window,

00:13:57.430 --> 00:14:00.660
looking at the street, her
right hand on her holstered gun,

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:02.870
her left hand holding
the radio to her ear.

00:14:02.870 --> 00:14:04.540
With her free ear,
she must have been

00:14:04.540 --> 00:14:06.350
listening for the sound
of Jens's suitcase

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:07.740
shutting and latching.

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:10.770
And when she didn't hear it,
she turned around and said,

00:14:10.770 --> 00:14:11.970
'Hurry.'

00:14:11.970 --> 00:14:14.120
Long before this, Jens
had been handed off

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:16.490
by the Danish Security
and Intelligence Service

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:19.690
to a series of agents who
spoke to Jens and each other

00:14:19.690 --> 00:14:22.140
in an accent that could have
meant they were Americans

00:14:22.140 --> 00:14:24.181
or could have meant they
learned to speak English

00:14:24.181 --> 00:14:25.820
from watching American TV.

00:14:25.820 --> 00:14:29.600
As for Jens, his English was
both unaccented and perfect,

00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:31.950
as it was, of course,
required to be

00:14:31.950 --> 00:14:34.440
by the Danish
educational system.

00:14:34.440 --> 00:14:36.190
He shut his suitcase
and asked her,

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:39.040
'Where are we going now?'
The agent looked back out

00:14:39.040 --> 00:14:42.180
the window and sighed in a way
that seemed intended to let

00:14:42.180 --> 00:14:45.660
Jens know how peeved she was
that he and his little cartoon

00:14:45.660 --> 00:14:48.610
had put her in a position where
she was forced to actually do

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:51.510
her incredibly boring
and dangerous job.

00:14:51.510 --> 00:14:53.870
'You know about as much
as I do,' she said.

00:14:53.870 --> 00:14:56.570
This, of course, was
completely untrue.

00:14:56.570 --> 00:14:58.740
As with everyone
who kept him safe,

00:14:58.740 --> 00:15:00.710
she knew exactly
why he had to leave

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:02.340
and where he was going next.

00:15:02.340 --> 00:15:04.090
As with every one
of his safekeepers,

00:15:04.090 --> 00:15:05.787
she never told
him what she knew,

00:15:05.787 --> 00:15:08.120
including why he had to keep
running if everyone thought

00:15:08.120 --> 00:15:09.580
he was already dead.

00:15:09.580 --> 00:15:11.970
'Credible threat,' was all
she would say when he asked.

00:15:11.970 --> 00:15:13.630
'There's a credible threat.'

00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:15.750
As with every one
of his safekeepers,

00:15:15.750 --> 00:15:18.057
this made Jens totally
dependent upon her.

00:15:18.057 --> 00:15:20.390
And it also made him fall in
love with her a little bit.

00:15:20.390 --> 00:15:22.680
And it also made him want
to go somewhere remote where

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:24.640
he would never see her again.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:27.300
'If you were me and you wanted
to go somewhere so remote that

00:15:27.300 --> 00:15:29.530
no one would ever find
you,' Jens asked her,

00:15:29.530 --> 00:15:32.520
'where would you run?'
Without hesitation, she said,

00:15:32.520 --> 00:15:35.180
'Broomeville.' 'Where?' he said.

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:36.960
'Exactly,' she said."

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:37.460
