00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:39.126
So this is about to
move to Broomeville.

00:15:39.126 --> 00:15:41.850
Broomeville's a town I made
up in upstate New York that's

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:43.900
a little bit modeled on
a town called Boonville

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:46.220
that I very cleverly
disguised by adding

00:15:46.220 --> 00:15:48.000
a consonant and a vowel.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.060
They're never going to find out.

00:15:50.060 --> 00:15:52.550
Yeah, this is Chapter 5.

00:15:52.550 --> 00:15:55.710
"Matty was in his office, even
though it was a Friday night.

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:58.080
Outside it was dark, dark.

00:15:58.080 --> 00:16:00.120
Inside, the overhead
lights were flickering

00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:02.910
like there were small animals
up there chewing on something

00:16:02.910 --> 00:16:05.130
important or just
running back and forth,

00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:06.880
enjoying their
Friday night, having

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:10.395
a good time messing around with
the long fluorescent tubes.

00:16:10.395 --> 00:16:12.770
'I'm not even supposed to be
thinking about you,' he said

00:16:12.770 --> 00:16:14.920
into his cellphone,
'let alone talking

00:16:14.920 --> 00:16:17.380
to you.' 'So don't
talk,' she said.

00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:19.120
'Just listen.'

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:20.430
So Matty did that.

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:22.585
She talked for a long
time, long enough

00:16:22.585 --> 00:16:25.210
for him to understand that after
she'd ended their affair seven

00:16:25.210 --> 00:16:27.370
years earlier,
she'd been so angry

00:16:27.370 --> 00:16:30.400
at him and at Broomeville,
and at the fucking world,

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:32.870
that she decided to
go work for the CIA,

00:16:32.870 --> 00:16:34.590
long enough for
him to understand

00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:37.290
that in her capacity
as a CIA agent,

00:16:37.290 --> 00:16:39.540
and his capacity as
an American citizen,

00:16:39.540 --> 00:16:41.970
she wanted him to
do her a favor,

00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:44.240
long enough for him to
get up out of his chair,

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:46.640
walk out of his office,
out of the building,

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:48.140
out into the parking lot.

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:51.430
He kept turning in circles
while he listened to her talk.

00:16:51.430 --> 00:16:54.460
Way off to the west was the
big dark nothing of the lake.

00:16:54.460 --> 00:16:57.300
To the east was the big dark
nothing of the mountains.

00:16:57.300 --> 00:17:00.220
A half mile to the north was
the town, the little square

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:02.270
that was actually more
like a trapezoid--

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:06.859
the gazebo, the monument, the
diner, the bar, the other bar,

00:17:06.859 --> 00:17:09.550
his house, which,
before they died,

00:17:09.550 --> 00:17:11.690
had been his parents'
house, the river that

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:13.670
eventually ran into the lake.

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:16.569
Right in front of him to the
south was the Broomeville,

00:17:16.569 --> 00:17:18.770
New York junior/senior
high school.

00:17:18.770 --> 00:17:20.520
But from where was she calling?

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:22.609
What direction was she?

00:17:22.609 --> 00:17:25.579
Anyway, when she was
done talking, Matty said,

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:28.210
'You've got to be kidding me.'
'You sound different,' she

00:17:28.210 --> 00:17:28.910
said.

00:17:28.910 --> 00:17:32.580
'Are you outside now or
something?' 'The CIA?' he said.

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:34.940
'I bet you're standing in
the parking lot,' she said.

00:17:34.940 --> 00:17:37.450
'How does someone just
end up in the CIA?'

00:17:37.450 --> 00:17:39.760
'The old Broomeville
junior/senior high parking

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:43.010
lot.' 'The sky is full
of stars here,' he said.

00:17:43.010 --> 00:17:45.890
'The sky is full of stars
here too,' she said.

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:49.550
'Are you outside?' 'No, but I'm
just guessing.' 'What exactly

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:52.040
did this guy do, anyway?'
'I can't tell you

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:54.110
that.' 'Why not?'

00:17:54.110 --> 00:17:56.069
She didn't say
anything right away.

00:17:56.069 --> 00:17:57.860
The only thing he could
hear was breathing,

00:17:57.860 --> 00:17:59.950
and he wondered, why
is it that when someone

00:17:59.950 --> 00:18:01.400
breathes in your
ear on the phone,

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:03.062
it's either sexy or sinister.

00:18:03.062 --> 00:18:04.520
But when someone
does it in person,

00:18:04.520 --> 00:18:06.480
it's mostly just annoying?

00:18:06.480 --> 00:18:09.130
'Because I don't want
to,' she finally said.

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:10.345
'Fair enough,' Matty said.

00:18:10.345 --> 00:18:12.075
And immediately, he
wished he hadn't.

00:18:12.075 --> 00:18:14.610
She had once accused
him of saying that,

00:18:14.610 --> 00:18:17.760
'fair enough,' way too often
and in response to things that

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:19.150
weren't fair enough at all.

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:20.774
And then they'd gotten
into a big fight

00:18:20.774 --> 00:18:23.840
about it, his just being, did
she have to be such a bitch?

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:25.370
And hers just
being, she wouldn't

00:18:25.370 --> 00:18:26.869
have to be such a
bitch if he didn't

00:18:26.869 --> 00:18:29.000
say 'fair enough' all the time.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.130
'There are no jobs,' he said.

00:18:31.130 --> 00:18:32.170
'Then fire someone.

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:34.670
There has to be at least one
person there who deserves to be

00:18:34.670 --> 00:18:37.310
fired.' 'There's
no one,' he said.

00:18:37.310 --> 00:18:40.270
But too late, he was
already thinking of someone.

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:43.670
'I'm not giving your buddy
a job,' he said, anyway.

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:45.770
'Any old job will do,' she said.

00:18:45.770 --> 00:18:49.550
'And he's not my buddy.'
'No,' Matty said.

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:51.110
'Let me just make two points.

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:53.510
He's an internationally
wanted criminal.' 'He's not

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:56.210
a criminal, Matthew,' she
said, 'unless being clueless is

00:18:56.210 --> 00:18:58.940
a crime.' 'But he is
internationally wanted,' Matty

00:18:58.940 --> 00:18:59.580
said.

00:18:59.580 --> 00:19:01.320
'People are trying
to assassinate him,

00:19:01.320 --> 00:19:03.540
and you want me to give
him a job in a school,

00:19:03.540 --> 00:19:05.300
a school full of children.'

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:07.030
'But that's one of
my points,' she said.

00:19:07.030 --> 00:19:09.100
'People are trying to
assassinate him here.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:11.190
People get assassinated
here all the time,

00:19:11.190 --> 00:19:13.010
but no one ever
gets assassinated

00:19:13.010 --> 00:19:16.240
in America.' 'What about Martin
Luther King Jr.?' he said.

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:17.920
'What about Abraham Lincoln?'

00:19:17.920 --> 00:19:20.480
'Well, there are obviously
exceptions,' she admitted.

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:23.460
'What about the Kennedys?'
'Fair enough,' she said.

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:25.080
And then they both laughed.

00:19:25.080 --> 00:19:26.990
'I have missed you,' Matty said.

00:19:26.990 --> 00:19:29.920
'That's my other
point,' she said."

