00:19:40.644 --> 00:19:42.060
I chose that because
no one really

00:19:42.060 --> 00:19:43.900
knows what the hell
guidance counselors do.

00:19:43.900 --> 00:19:45.510
And so I'd seen them as
the most mysterious job

00:19:45.510 --> 00:19:47.280
I could give him, in
my opinion, at least.

00:19:47.280 --> 00:19:48.600
I've just offended
probably someone

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:49.690
who's related to a
guidance counselor.

00:19:49.690 --> 00:19:51.481
I actually gave a talk
once, and this woman

00:19:51.481 --> 00:19:53.060
got up at that
moment-- when I just

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:54.030
said that-- and walked out.

00:19:54.030 --> 00:19:56.155
And she was a guidance
counselor, as it turned out.

00:19:56.155 --> 00:19:58.230
So you'd think I would learn.

00:19:58.230 --> 00:20:00.840
And I haven't learned.

00:20:00.840 --> 00:20:05.680
And then so fast forward a
few days, and Jens shows up.

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:08.980
His identity is--
he's now Henry Larson.

00:20:08.980 --> 00:20:10.210
He's got a fake name.

00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:14.020
And he's also pretending to
be a Swede and not a Dane

00:20:14.020 --> 00:20:16.560
because the theory is his
English is too good to be

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:18.000
anything but a Swede or a Dane.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.480
And so obviously, it's
better to be a Swede.

00:20:21.480 --> 00:20:21.980
Yeah.

00:20:21.980 --> 00:20:23.130
Matty's the principal.

00:20:23.130 --> 00:20:25.020
That you have.

00:20:25.020 --> 00:20:29.710
And Henry/Jens is now speaking
to Matty's wife, Ellen,

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:32.680
who's the owner and proprietor
of the bar, the Lumber Lodge,

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:36.480
in town, one of the two bars.

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:37.230
Everyone got that?

00:20:37.230 --> 00:20:37.871
Yeah.

00:20:37.871 --> 00:20:38.370
It's real.

00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:41.430
It's an autobiographical
novel, clearly.

00:20:41.430 --> 00:20:43.410
"By the time they got
outside the Lumber Lodge,

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:44.710
it was snowing.

00:20:44.710 --> 00:20:47.940
'Snowing?' Evidently,
Ellen felt the same way.

00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:49.370
'Snowing,' she said.

00:20:49.370 --> 00:20:52.320
But then she looked up and
got a snowflake in the eye.

00:20:52.320 --> 00:20:53.710
'Oh, wow,' she said.

00:20:53.710 --> 00:20:55.310
She blinked rapidly
and then began

00:20:55.310 --> 00:20:57.580
tugging at the underside
of her right eye.

00:20:57.580 --> 00:20:59.120
'Does it hurt?' Henry asked.

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:01.720
'It's only snow,'
Ellen said, 'but yeah,

00:21:01.720 --> 00:21:03.010
it does hurt a little.'

00:21:03.010 --> 00:21:06.760
She tugged her eye again, then
blinked slowly, once, twice,

00:21:06.760 --> 00:21:07.690
three times.

00:21:07.690 --> 00:21:10.160
'I really should wear
glasses,' she said.

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:13.207
'They would protect your eyes
from the snow,' Henry said.

00:21:13.207 --> 00:21:15.290
And Ellen blinked once
more and then looked at him

00:21:15.290 --> 00:21:16.650
with wide eyes.

00:21:16.650 --> 00:21:18.920
'Instead of
contacts,' Ellen said.

00:21:18.920 --> 00:21:20.287
'Contacts?' Henry thought.

00:21:20.287 --> 00:21:22.120
And then he thought--"
this will be obvious,

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:25.460
I don't speak Danish, in a
second-- "and then he thought,

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:27.660
'Kontaktlinsers.'
He wore them too,

00:21:27.660 --> 00:21:29.840
special kontaktlinsers
that helped correct his

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:33.630
nearsightedness and also
made his blue eyes brown.

00:21:33.630 --> 00:21:36.030
Anyway, it apparently had
been snowing for a while

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:38.250
because there was a rusty
blue pickup truck parked

00:21:38.250 --> 00:21:40.390
in front of the Lumber
Lodge, and its windshield

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:41.970
was covered with snow.

00:21:41.970 --> 00:21:44.730
Ellen got into the driver's
side of the truck and Henry

00:21:44.730 --> 00:21:46.440
into the passenger side.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:49.220
Ellen then did several
things in quick succession.

00:21:49.220 --> 00:21:51.090
First, she put the
key into the ignition

00:21:51.090 --> 00:21:52.880
and turned it, which
started the truck

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:55.040
with a roar and then a rattle.

00:21:55.040 --> 00:21:57.030
Then she turned the
windshield wipers on,

00:21:57.030 --> 00:22:01.620
but the snow was crusted on the
glass and wouldn't wipe off.

00:22:01.620 --> 00:22:03.270
Henry offered to
get out and scrape,

00:22:03.270 --> 00:22:04.750
but Ellen waved him off.

00:22:04.750 --> 00:22:06.570
'It's cold out there,' she said.

00:22:06.570 --> 00:22:08.690
Then Ellen turned
on the defrost,

00:22:08.690 --> 00:22:11.170
and cold air came
blasting into the truck.

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:13.080
Then she turned on the radio.

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:14.550
A man's voice came out.

00:22:14.550 --> 00:22:16.220
He was talking
about the weather.

00:22:16.220 --> 00:22:17.630
They listened for a few seconds.

00:22:17.630 --> 00:22:19.670
And then Ellen punched
a button on the radio,

00:22:19.670 --> 00:22:21.800
and another man's
voice came out.

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:23.470
Henry recognized it immediately.

00:22:23.470 --> 00:22:25.400
Sports talk radio
sounds the same

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:27.070
no matter what
language it's spoken in

00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:29.390
and what sport is
being discussed.

00:22:29.390 --> 00:22:31.330
They listened to that
for a few seconds.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:33.120
And then Ellen punched
another button,

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:36.810
and another man's voice came
out talking about politics.

00:22:36.810 --> 00:22:38.810
After a few seconds
of listening to that,

00:22:38.810 --> 00:22:40.550
Ellen turned off the radio.

00:22:40.550 --> 00:22:42.560
She lit a cigarette
and smoked it halfway

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:44.980
to the filter before
glancing at Henry.

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:47.740
The glance was half
dare, half apology.

00:22:47.740 --> 00:22:50.730
'Matty doesn't like to
see me smoke,' she said.

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:52.930
Finally, she put
the car in gear.

00:22:52.930 --> 00:22:55.260
To Henry, all this
seemed like preparations

00:22:55.260 --> 00:22:56.780
for a very long journey.

00:22:56.780 --> 00:22:59.340
But not even a minute later,
Ellen stopped the truck

00:22:59.340 --> 00:23:02.080
and said, 'We're here.'

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:04.410
In this way, Henry
learned several things,

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:07.250
that once Americans were out of
the cold and in their trucks,

00:23:07.250 --> 00:23:09.474
they did not like to get
back out into the cold,

00:23:09.474 --> 00:23:11.890
even if it meant making the
inside of their trucks as cold

00:23:11.890 --> 00:23:14.700
as the outside, that American
weathermen like to refer

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:18.430
to snow as 'the white stuff,'
that American sports talk radio

00:23:18.430 --> 00:23:20.370
announcers like to
say about something,

00:23:20.370 --> 00:23:22.520
'there's no doubt about
it,' before then expressing

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:25.650
their many doubts about it, that
American political commentators

00:23:25.650 --> 00:23:27.360
like to preface their
comments by saying,

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:30.400
'no offense,' before then
saying something offensive.

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:33.200
The political commentator on the
radio had said to whomever he

00:23:33.200 --> 00:23:36.330
was talking to, 'No offense,
but you have to be the stupidest

00:23:36.330 --> 00:23:38.210
human being on the planet.'

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:40.010
That Americans were
very impatient people

00:23:40.010 --> 00:23:42.724
with very short attention
spans, that Americans believed

00:23:42.724 --> 00:23:44.640
that as long as they
were inside their trucks,

00:23:44.640 --> 00:23:47.260
they were invisible, that as
long as they smoked cigarettes

00:23:47.260 --> 00:23:48.926
inside their trucks,
they would not then

00:23:48.926 --> 00:23:51.290
smell like cigarettes once
they exited their trucks,

00:23:51.290 --> 00:23:53.665
and that, in general, Americans
thought their trucks were

00:23:53.665 --> 00:23:56.070
magic, that while
Europeans tended to think

00:23:56.070 --> 00:23:58.590
of Americans as people who
like to drive incredibly

00:23:58.590 --> 00:24:01.217
long distances in their
pickup trucks, in fact,

00:24:01.217 --> 00:24:03.300
Americans like to drive
incredibly short distances

00:24:03.300 --> 00:24:05.120
in their trucks as well.

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:07.750
These were the lessons Henry
learned about Americans

00:24:07.750 --> 00:24:09.780
during his first minute
in Ellen's truck.

00:24:09.780 --> 00:24:12.700
And not once was he forced
to reconsider them during all

00:24:12.700 --> 00:24:15.160
his days in Broomeville.

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:18.590
Ellen put the truck in park, but
its engine was still running,

00:24:18.590 --> 00:24:20.140
its wipers still wiping.

00:24:20.140 --> 00:24:22.570
It was difficult to
see anything but snow.

00:24:22.570 --> 00:24:24.680
The truck headlights
were full of it.

00:24:24.680 --> 00:24:26.970
'Does it always snow this
much here?' he asked.

00:24:26.970 --> 00:24:27.520
'Why?

00:24:27.520 --> 00:24:30.740
Doesn't it snow like this where
you're from too?' 'No,' Henry

00:24:30.740 --> 00:24:31.740
said.

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:35.650
'Really?' Ellen said, 'because
when I see Sweden, I see snow.'

00:24:35.650 --> 00:24:37.310
'Of course, of
course,' Henry said.

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:40.470
'But then, I'm from southern
Sweden.' 'It doesn't snow

00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:43.030
in southern Sweden?'
'It does, but not often

00:24:43.030 --> 00:24:46.330
in October.' 'It doesn't usually
snow this much in October here

00:24:46.330 --> 00:24:47.830
either,' Ellen said.

00:24:47.830 --> 00:24:50.200
She turned off the truck
and the headlights too.

00:24:50.200 --> 00:24:51.770
But still, there was snow.

00:24:51.770 --> 00:24:54.680
Still, there was light, not
too far in front of them

00:24:54.680 --> 00:24:58.070
and much higher off the
ground, a ring of light towers.

00:24:58.070 --> 00:24:59.450
Henry supposed
they had something

00:24:59.450 --> 00:25:01.160
to do with this baseball game.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:03.600
In a moment, he and Ellen
would get out of the car

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:05.550
and start walking
in that direction.

00:25:05.550 --> 00:25:06.550
And what then?

00:25:06.550 --> 00:25:08.790
Something is about to
happen, Henry thought.

00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:10.124
But what is about to happen?

00:25:10.124 --> 00:25:11.790
He wanted to reach
across the bench seat

00:25:11.790 --> 00:25:13.290
to grab Ellen's hand.

00:25:13.290 --> 00:25:16.820
But instead, he said, 'It's
beautiful.' 'Snow is always

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:18.960
beautiful in October,' she said.

00:25:18.960 --> 00:25:21.237
'I really think I'm going
to like it here,' he said.

00:25:21.237 --> 00:25:23.320
'OK, listen,' Ellen said.
'You shouldn't talk like

00:25:23.320 --> 00:25:26.030
that.' 'Talk like
what?' Henry asked.

00:25:26.030 --> 00:25:28.870
He seemed genuinely, almost
pedagogically concerned.

00:25:28.870 --> 00:25:30.685
And if he had a
pad of paper, Ellen

00:25:30.685 --> 00:25:33.580
was sure he would have started
taking notes on the subject.

00:25:33.580 --> 00:25:35.930
In fact, he reached
into his jacket pocket

00:25:35.930 --> 00:25:39.000
as though looking for
something to write on and with.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.200
And then he reached into
the other jacket pocket.

00:25:41.200 --> 00:25:43.040
There was clearly
nothing in either.

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:45.470
Then he looked even
more concerned.

00:25:45.470 --> 00:25:48.640
Ellen didn't think she'd ever
seen a face like that, so wide

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:49.390
open.

00:25:49.390 --> 00:25:50.860
Ellen didn't think
she'd ever seen

00:25:50.860 --> 00:25:52.940
someone who clearly
wanted advice,

00:25:52.940 --> 00:25:54.700
who wanted to be helped.

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:57.550
'Like you talk,' Ellen said, 'I
really think I'm going to like

00:25:57.550 --> 00:25:58.091
it here.

00:25:58.091 --> 00:26:00.340
If you say things like that,
these people will eat you

00:26:00.340 --> 00:26:04.960
alive.' 'Even the students?'
'Especially them.' 'What should

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:08.461
I say?' 'Maybe you shouldn't
say anything,' she said.

00:26:08.461 --> 00:26:10.710
Ellen remembered when Kurt--"
Kurt's her teenage son--

00:26:10.710 --> 00:26:11.920
"when Kurt was younger.

00:26:11.920 --> 00:26:13.545
She would say something
he didn't like,

00:26:13.545 --> 00:26:16.220
and he would just stand
there with his arms crossed,

00:26:16.220 --> 00:26:18.640
frowning, evidently waiting
for her to say something

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:21.030
else, which she inevitably did.

00:26:21.030 --> 00:26:22.750
She explained this to Henry.

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:24.730
'You should just go
like this,' she said.

00:26:24.730 --> 00:26:26.250
And then she demonstrated.

00:26:26.250 --> 00:26:27.450
Henry did it back.

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:29.920
And when he did, Ellen
thought of a younger Kurt,

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:32.180
and a younger Matty,
and a younger self.

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:34.130
Then suddenly, she
became so lonely

00:26:34.130 --> 00:26:36.540
for that time and those people.

00:26:36.540 --> 00:26:38.230
'Are you all
right?' Henry asked.

00:26:38.230 --> 00:26:40.370
'I've been a little
lonely,' she said.

00:26:40.370 --> 00:26:42.020
Henry didn't say anything back.

00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:43.520
He just frowned at
her, as though he

00:26:43.520 --> 00:26:46.380
disapproved of the inaccuracy
of her declaration.

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:48.000
'I'm so lonely,' she said.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:51.930
'I've been so lonely for
such a long time.' Still,

00:26:51.930 --> 00:26:53.210
Henry frowned.

00:26:53.210 --> 00:26:54.760
Ellen remembered this now.

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:57.100
She remembered feeling that
she would have done anything

00:26:57.100 --> 00:26:59.990
or said anything to get
that look off Kurt's face,

00:26:59.990 --> 00:27:01.330
even tell the truth.

00:27:01.330 --> 00:27:03.900
'I've been so lonely, ever
since Matty told me he'd been

00:27:03.900 --> 00:27:06.470
cheating on me.' The
frown disappeared.

00:27:06.470 --> 00:27:09.810
'That's more like it,'
Henry's face seemed to say."

00:27:09.810 --> 00:27:11.220
OK.

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:15.030
Two years later, Henry is
engaged to be married to Ellen.

00:27:15.030 --> 00:27:15.950
Ellen has left Matty.

00:27:15.950 --> 00:27:17.825
And this becomes more
and more soap opera-ish

00:27:17.825 --> 00:27:18.930
the more I speak about it.

00:27:18.930 --> 00:27:22.515
And anyways, Tarik, who's the
young man who's burned down

00:27:22.515 --> 00:27:24.390
the cartoonist's house
is wracked with guilt,

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:26.265
because he thinks he's
killed the cartoonist.

00:27:26.265 --> 00:27:30.160
And so he's going to hunt
down-- find what he thinks

00:27:30.160 --> 00:27:31.799
is the widow and confess to her.

00:27:31.799 --> 00:27:33.340
He's not been arrested
all this time.

00:27:33.340 --> 00:27:35.130
The high school, by
the way, that Henry's

00:27:35.130 --> 00:27:36.940
about to be employed
in or is employed in,

00:27:36.940 --> 00:27:40.370
is full of CIA agents who
are posing as social studies

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:44.619
teachers, and
janitors, and such.

00:27:44.619 --> 00:27:46.160
It's a ridiculous
book, if that's not

00:27:46.160 --> 00:27:47.880
totally clear by now.

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:49.280
All right, I said, Tarik.

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:49.870
I'm sorry.

00:27:49.870 --> 00:27:51.661
Tarik is one of the
two men who burned down

00:27:51.661 --> 00:27:52.710
the newspaper's offices.

00:27:52.710 --> 00:27:57.350
Soren is the guy who's
about to apologize.

00:27:57.350 --> 00:27:59.600
"Soren thought it would
probably be difficult to find

00:27:59.600 --> 00:28:02.606
the address of the widow of
a cartoonist whom he murdered

00:28:02.606 --> 00:28:03.980
in what the
newspapers had called

00:28:03.980 --> 00:28:06.846
a 'terrorist firebombing.'
But that was not the case.

00:28:06.846 --> 00:28:09.220
It hadn't been difficult to
find the cartoonist's address

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:09.854
either.

00:28:09.854 --> 00:28:11.270
It hadn't been
difficult for Soren

00:28:11.270 --> 00:28:13.220
to burn his house
down or for Tarik

00:28:13.220 --> 00:28:15.260
to burn down the
newspaper's offices.

00:28:15.260 --> 00:28:17.610
It hadn't even been difficult
for them to escape capture

00:28:17.610 --> 00:28:19.910
after the firebombing,
after the newspapers had

00:28:19.910 --> 00:28:23.604
reported that the cartoonist had
died in the fire Soren had set.

00:28:23.604 --> 00:28:26.145
No one from the police or the
Danish Security or Intelligence

00:28:26.145 --> 00:28:28.320
Service had ever
questioned them,

00:28:28.320 --> 00:28:30.622
even though there were
barely any Muslims in Skagen,

00:28:30.622 --> 00:28:32.830
and even though it had been
the only murder committed

00:28:32.830 --> 00:28:36.610
in Skagen that year, and the
year before that, and so on.

00:28:36.610 --> 00:28:40.480
'Murder, murder, blood, blood,'
that was the difficult part,

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:42.980
having the words 'murder' and
'blood' crawl through his head

00:28:42.980 --> 00:28:44.277
for the past four years.

00:28:44.277 --> 00:28:45.860
Although he supposed
the murder hadn't

00:28:45.860 --> 00:28:47.830
been easy for the
cartoonist either,

00:28:47.830 --> 00:28:49.500
not to mention his widow.

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:52.840
Anyway, she lived in Aarhus,
just a couple of hours south.

00:28:52.840 --> 00:28:55.300
The newspaper reports
had given him her name.

00:28:55.300 --> 00:28:57.490
The internet had
given him her address

00:28:57.490 --> 00:28:59.460
and then directions
how to get there.

00:28:59.460 --> 00:29:03.030
But first, Soren had to
borrow his dad's car.

00:29:03.030 --> 00:29:05.630
So he went home, which was less
than a mile from the boatyard

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:08.840
where he and Tarik worked,
right across the street from OC

00:29:08.840 --> 00:29:12.370
Trawl, where his father
worked making fishing nets.

00:29:12.370 --> 00:29:14.590
His house was the house in
which Soren had grown up

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:16.840
and in which he still lived.

00:29:16.840 --> 00:29:20.000
It was yellow, of course, and
had a red tile roof, also,

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:20.980
of course.

00:29:20.980 --> 00:29:23.350
His parents' names
were Faruk and Benan,

00:29:23.350 --> 00:29:25.950
but they had named him Soren,
although their last name was

00:29:25.950 --> 00:29:27.060
Korkmaz.

00:29:27.060 --> 00:29:29.810
As far as Soren
was concerned, they

00:29:29.810 --> 00:29:33.240
might as well have named
him Dane, Son of Turks.

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:35.027
Soren walked in the front door.

00:29:35.027 --> 00:29:36.860
His father was sitting
on the couch watching

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:39.030
professional handball on TV.

00:29:39.030 --> 00:29:40.957
Handball was his
father's favorite sport,

00:29:40.957 --> 00:29:43.540
even though he didn't understand
the rules because pretty much

00:29:43.540 --> 00:29:45.390
no one understood the rules.

00:29:45.390 --> 00:29:49.230
You were allowed to run and leap
and catch and hurl the ball,

00:29:49.230 --> 00:29:53.030
except in some circumstances,
for some mysterious reasons,

00:29:53.030 --> 00:29:55.430
when these activities
were forbidden.

00:29:55.430 --> 00:29:57.910
'Kolding and Aalborg,'
Soren's father said.

00:29:57.910 --> 00:30:01.610
'Don't tell me who won' 'What?'
'It was actually played last

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:03.080
night,' Soren's father said.

00:30:03.080 --> 00:30:04.740
They were playing it on TV now.

00:30:04.740 --> 00:30:06.430
'Don't tell me who won.'

00:30:06.430 --> 00:30:08.540
Soren sat down next
to his father, who

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:12.520
smelled of salt and fish,
even though the nets he made

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:14.150
hadn't yet touch the sea.

00:30:14.150 --> 00:30:16.940
Or maybe it was Soren
himself who smelled that way.

00:30:16.940 --> 00:30:18.790
He watched the
handball for a minute.

00:30:18.790 --> 00:30:20.820
But then it started
to hurt his eyes,

00:30:20.820 --> 00:30:22.670
so he looked out
the front window.

00:30:22.670 --> 00:30:25.364
It was dark and darker
still with the fog, which

00:30:25.364 --> 00:30:26.530
came right up to the window.

00:30:29.890 --> 00:30:32.770
A deep-throated horn
blew out there somewhere,

00:30:32.770 --> 00:30:34.400
and the fog seemed
to get somehow

00:30:34.400 --> 00:30:36.086
even thicker against the pane.

00:30:36.086 --> 00:30:37.460
It was one of
those times when it

00:30:37.460 --> 00:30:40.200
was difficult to imagine
that it wasn't 6 o'clock

00:30:40.200 --> 00:30:41.870
everywhere in the world.

00:30:41.870 --> 00:30:45.200
Soren turned back to the TV and
saw a bunch of rangey white men

00:30:45.200 --> 00:30:48.500
in knee and elbow pads,
hugging each other.

00:30:48.500 --> 00:30:50.070
'Goal?' he said.

00:30:50.070 --> 00:30:52.330
'I believe so,' his father said.

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:54.350
'I don't know how you
can watch this stuff.'

00:30:54.350 --> 00:30:55.500
His father shrugged.

00:30:55.500 --> 00:30:57.700
'It's better than
making nets,' he said.

00:30:57.700 --> 00:31:00.740
This was the way Soren's
father had always talked.

00:31:00.740 --> 00:31:03.320
Something was always
better than something else.

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:06.680
When his wife, Soren's mother,
had died several years earlier

00:31:06.680 --> 00:31:09.870
of breast cancer, he'd gone
back to work making nets the day

00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:10.382
after.

00:31:10.382 --> 00:31:12.840
And when someone had asked him
how he could go back to work

00:31:12.840 --> 00:31:15.630
making nets so soon
after his wife's death,

00:31:15.630 --> 00:31:19.240
he had shrugged and said, 'It's
better than sitting at home.'

00:31:19.240 --> 00:31:21.530
'Can I borrow the car tomorrow
morning?' Soren asked.

00:31:21.530 --> 00:31:24.960
And then he added, 'Don't look
at me like that.' 'Look at you

00:31:24.960 --> 00:31:29.010
like what?' Soren's father said,
still looking at him like that.

00:31:29.010 --> 00:31:31.630
His father's look, it
had always been there.

00:31:31.630 --> 00:31:34.520
But it had gotten more
intense, more squirm-inducing,

00:31:34.520 --> 00:31:36.740
more knowing, since
Soren had accidentally

00:31:36.740 --> 00:31:38.350
murdered the cartoonist.

00:31:38.350 --> 00:31:40.321
Or was that just
Soren's imagination?

00:31:40.321 --> 00:31:42.820
In any case, Soren didn't know
how much longer he could take

00:31:42.820 --> 00:31:46.230
it, the look, the look, the look
that was made up of a litanies

00:31:46.230 --> 00:31:47.290
of don'ts.

00:31:47.290 --> 00:31:48.440
Don't disappoint me.

00:31:48.440 --> 00:31:49.710
Don't make me look bad.

00:31:49.710 --> 00:31:51.246
Don't make your people look bad.

00:31:51.246 --> 00:31:52.870
Don't you know we
moved to this country

00:31:52.870 --> 00:31:54.470
so you would be your own person?

00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:56.070
Don't be someone else's person.

00:31:56.070 --> 00:31:57.560
Don't forget that you're my son.

00:31:57.560 --> 00:31:59.010
Don't do anything stupid.

00:31:59.010 --> 00:32:00.140
Don't hurt the car.

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:01.260
Don't hurt yourself.

00:32:01.260 --> 00:32:02.885
Don't you know that
your mother told me

00:32:02.885 --> 00:32:04.970
before she died not to let
anything happen to you?

00:32:04.970 --> 00:32:07.590
Don't you know I'd die if
something happened to you?

00:32:07.590 --> 00:32:08.900
Don't make me die.

00:32:08.900 --> 00:32:09.870
Don't kill me.

00:32:09.870 --> 00:32:11.160
Don't kill yourself.

00:32:11.160 --> 00:32:12.350
Don't kill anyone else.

00:32:12.350 --> 00:32:13.800
Don't get caught if you do.

00:32:13.800 --> 00:32:15.060
Don't do anything terrible.

00:32:15.060 --> 00:32:17.560
Don't you know that I love you
no matter what terrible thing

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:18.400
you've done?

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:19.480
Don't forget that.

00:32:19.480 --> 00:32:20.840
Don't do it again.

00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:21.980
Don't make it worse.

00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:24.350
Don't you know I know
everything about you?

00:32:24.350 --> 00:32:26.460
Don't cry, for crying out loud.

00:32:26.460 --> 00:32:28.360
Don't cry, because
then I'll cry.

00:32:28.360 --> 00:32:31.930
Just don't, don't, do not.

00:32:31.930 --> 00:32:35.010
'Just don't forget to put gas in
the car.' Soren's father said.

00:32:35.010 --> 00:32:37.490
And then he turned
back to his handball."

00:32:37.490 --> 00:32:40.210
I'm going to stop
there, I think.

00:32:40.210 --> 00:32:44.600
And I would be happy to take any
questions if you all have them.

00:32:44.600 --> 00:32:46.170
So what happens
then, briefly, is

00:32:46.170 --> 00:32:50.540
that the CIA agent, for a number
of reasons that only exist

00:32:50.540 --> 00:32:54.300
in novels, makes
Soren-- blackmails him

00:32:54.300 --> 00:32:58.670
into going to Broomefield
to try to kill Henry.

00:32:58.670 --> 00:33:02.030
And, yeah, that's the last
half of the book, the series

00:33:02.030 --> 00:33:04.420
of stories connected to that.

00:33:04.420 --> 00:33:05.030
Yeah.

00:33:05.030 --> 00:33:07.321
So I'd be happy to answer
questions if anyone has them.

00:33:10.335 --> 00:33:12.210
I mean, the question
would be, what the fuck?

00:33:12.210 --> 00:33:12.960
Right?

00:33:12.960 --> 00:33:14.290
That's the operative question.

00:33:14.290 --> 00:33:15.660
Were you saying yes back there?

00:33:15.660 --> 00:33:16.600
Is that your hand like that?

00:33:16.600 --> 00:33:17.100
Yeah.

00:33:17.100 --> 00:33:17.840
Yeah.

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:19.423
AUDIENCE: I guess
I'll ask a question.

00:33:19.423 --> 00:33:20.910
BROCK CLARKE: Yeah, sure.

00:33:20.910 --> 00:33:22.566
AUDIENCE: Where
does it come from?

00:33:22.566 --> 00:33:24.645
Did it start fully
formed as a story?

00:33:24.645 --> 00:33:26.270
Did it start as an
idea of a character?

00:33:26.270 --> 00:33:27.670
How does it--

00:33:27.670 --> 00:33:31.430
BROCK CLARKE: It began
with my brief experience

00:33:31.430 --> 00:33:33.722
in Denmark, thinking about
it as the happiest place

00:33:33.722 --> 00:33:36.180
in the world, the home of the
happiest people in the world,

00:33:36.180 --> 00:33:39.880
and the irony of these cartoons
being drawn there, making

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:41.575
these people really unhappy.

00:33:41.575 --> 00:33:43.840
But again, then I began
to think about my-- I

00:33:43.840 --> 00:33:46.930
quickly-- so I wanted
this book to exist

00:33:46.930 --> 00:33:49.830
not as a reaction, a
commentary on the cartoons,

00:33:49.830 --> 00:33:52.290
the reactions to the
commentary, but a story

00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:54.680
of these characters whose
lives had sort of gotten out

00:33:54.680 --> 00:33:57.689
of their control, and
partly, because they didn't

00:33:57.689 --> 00:33:58.980
realize they had other options.

00:33:58.980 --> 00:34:01.260
They believed that what
they did were inevitable

00:34:01.260 --> 00:34:02.427
and couldn't be objected to.

00:34:02.427 --> 00:34:04.635
And then once they realized
they were not inevitable,

00:34:04.635 --> 00:34:05.920
it was too late to fix them.

00:34:05.920 --> 00:34:08.139
I guess my novels and
my stories are always

00:34:08.139 --> 00:34:11.190
about people who don't realize
that there are other options.

00:34:11.190 --> 00:34:12.750
And then they're
the stories of them

00:34:12.750 --> 00:34:15.841
trying to live their lives,
despite the bad choices they've

00:34:15.841 --> 00:34:16.340
made.

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:19.030
And then I just don't let them
because you set characters

00:34:19.030 --> 00:34:19.967
on a path.

00:34:19.967 --> 00:34:21.550
Then you should
actually let them stay

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:22.770
on that path, no matter what.

00:34:22.770 --> 00:34:26.300
I guess maybe the other
question is, why send

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:29.346
this guy to upstate New York?

00:34:29.346 --> 00:34:30.929
Part of the answer's
autobiographical.

00:34:30.929 --> 00:34:33.969
I'm from there, and I like
the cheap irony of someone

00:34:33.969 --> 00:34:35.719
from the happiest place
in the world going

00:34:35.719 --> 00:34:37.190
to the home of the
least happy people

00:34:37.190 --> 00:34:38.929
in the world, which is my
experience with upstate New

00:34:38.929 --> 00:34:39.739
York.

00:34:39.739 --> 00:34:42.239
I think perversely, that makes
me happy to be there, though.

00:34:42.239 --> 00:34:44.300
I like grouchy people.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:45.920
I also wanted to
write a spy novel

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:47.880
in which the spies were
bumblers and in which

00:34:47.880 --> 00:34:52.579
the locales of the novel
were not Paris, Istanbul.

00:34:52.579 --> 00:34:53.870
They were not someplace exotic.

00:34:53.870 --> 00:34:59.230
They were someplace that the
world had forgot, and partly,

00:34:59.230 --> 00:35:01.550
to give myself a chance to
write about these places

00:35:01.550 --> 00:35:03.675
that no one in the world
really cares about, which,

00:35:03.675 --> 00:35:04.870
for me, is upstate New York.

00:35:04.870 --> 00:35:06.500
And the irony for me
is I wanted to see what

00:35:06.500 --> 00:35:07.850
this cartoonist would be like.

00:35:07.850 --> 00:35:10.050
He's gotten a new lease on life
in this terrible place, which

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:11.680
makes him really
happy for a while.

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:14.560
And I wanted to see what
effect he would have

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:16.580
on the people in that town.

00:35:16.580 --> 00:35:19.560
I mean, I also wanted it to be
about American surveillance,

00:35:19.560 --> 00:35:20.540
American violence.

00:35:20.540 --> 00:35:21.999
It's, by far, the
most violent book

00:35:21.999 --> 00:35:23.831
I've ever written,
although you don't see it

00:35:23.831 --> 00:35:25.111
in any of the chapters I read.

00:35:25.111 --> 00:35:27.610
I wanted to see-- I wanted to
think about these things going

00:35:27.610 --> 00:35:28.985
on in America,
but I did not want

00:35:28.985 --> 00:35:31.460
to do a straightforward
commentary on those things.

00:35:31.460 --> 00:35:34.282
I wanted to do things that would
surprise the people who maybe

00:35:34.282 --> 00:35:36.115
had made up their minds
about these cartoons

00:35:36.115 --> 00:35:39.240
and the cartoonists
coming into the book.

00:35:39.240 --> 00:35:42.360
It's a long, convoluted answer
to a really precise question.

00:35:42.360 --> 00:35:42.930
Thank you.

00:35:42.930 --> 00:35:44.346
It's been really
great to be here.

00:35:44.346 --> 00:35:46.385
And, yeah, thank
you for having me.

00:35:46.385 --> 00:35:47.260
Thanks for listening.

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:47.926
I appreciate it.

00:35:47.926 --> 00:35:48.920
Thanks.

00:35:48.920 --> 00:35:50.320
